👇

🔐 OAuth 2.0 + OpenID Connect (From Scratch)

A minimal implementation of OAuth 2.0 Authorization Code Flow with OpenID Connect, built from scratch to deeply understand how authentication and authorization systems work under the hood.

🚀 Overview

This project is an attempt to move beyond using OAuth libraries and instead understand the full flow by building it manually.

It covers:

Client Registration
User Authentication
Authorization (Consent Flow)
Authorization Code Generation
Token Exchange (/token)
Access Token Usage (/userinfo)
Basic OpenID Connect (id_token)
🧠 Motivation

OAuth 2.0 is widely used, but often treated as a black box.

This project focuses on:

Understanding how each component interacts rather than just using it.

Building this system helped clarify:

Why authorization codes exist
Why token exchange is server-to-server
How trust is established between client and server
🏗️ Architecture

The system includes:

Authorization Server
Handles login, consent, token issuance
Resource Server
Serves protected endpoints (/userinfo)
Client (Test App)
Simulates a third-party application
🔁 Full Flow

1. Client Registration
   Client registers and receives:
   client_id
   client_secret
2. User Authentication
   User signs up / logs in
   Session is established (JWT / cookie)
3. Authorization Request
   GET /authorize?client_id=...&redirect_uri=...&scope=...&state=...
   Server validates client
   Checks user session
   Redirects to login if needed
4. Consent Screen

User is asked to approve or deny access.

5. Authorization Code

If approved:

Server generates a short-lived code
Stores:
userId
clientId
scope
expiry

Redirect:

redirect_uri?code=abc123&state=xyz 6. Token Exchange (Server-to-Server)
POST /token

Body:

{
"client_id": "...",
"client_secret": "...",
"code": "...",
"redirect_uri": "..."
} 7. Validation

Server verifies:

Client credentials
Authorization code
Redirect URI match
Expiry

Then:

Deletes code (one-time use) 8. Token Issuance

Response:

{
"access_token": "...",
"id_token": "...",
"token_type": "Bearer",
"expires_in": 3600
} 9. Accessing Protected Resources
GET /userinfo
Authorization: Bearer <access_token>

Returns:

{
"userId": "...",
"email": "..."
}
🔑 Key Concepts Learned
OAuth ≠ Login
Separation of:
Authentication (who the user is)
Authorization (what the client can access)
/authorize vs /token distinction:
/authorize → user interaction
/token → server-to-server
Authorization codes are:
short-lived
one-time use
⚠️ Limitations (Intentional)

This is a learning-focused implementation, so it does not include:

PKCE (Proof Key for Code Exchange)
Refresh tokens
Advanced security hardening
Production-grade key management
🛠️ Tech Stack
Node.js
Express
MongoDB
JWT
bcrypt
React
Vite

🖥️ Separate React Frontend

This repo now includes a separate Vite React app inside:

frontend/

Backend auth server:

npm install
npm run dev

Frontend app:

cd frontend
npm install
npm run dev

Default URLs:

Backend: http://localhost:8000
Frontend: http://localhost:5173

Make sure backend .env includes:

FRONTEND_URL=http://localhost:5173
ISSUER=http://localhost:8000

The React UI includes:

User signup
User login/logout
OAuth client registration
Consent screen
OAuth authorization URL tester
OAuth callback page
Session dashboard

OpenID Connect discovery endpoints:

GET /.well-known/openid-configuration
GET /.well-known/jwks.json

The access token is still signed with the local JWT secret for API protection.
The ID token is signed with RS256 and can be verified through the JWKS public key.
If OIDC_CERT is configured, the JWKS also exposes the certificate chain through x5c.

Generate a local certificate/key pair:

openssl genpkey -algorithm RSA -out private.pem -pkeyopt rsa_keygen_bits:2048
openssl req -new -x509 -key private.pem -out cert.pem -days 365 -subj "/CN=OpenID Mini"
openssl x509 -in cert.pem -pubkey -noout > public.pem

